<section class="section-gap">
  <div class="container-shell">
    <p class="eyebrow">Why current sourcing takes too much time</p>
    <h2 class="h2 mt-5">Too many tabs. Too much manual comparison. Too much spreadsheet work.</h2>
    <p class="subcopy">
      Most import workflows are still fragmented. Teams jump between marketplaces, compare listings manually, and
      calculate landed cost in separate spreadsheets before they can decide what is worth pursuing.
    </p>

    <div class="mt-10 grid gap-4 md:grid-cols-2 xl:grid-cols-3">
      <article class="card">
        <h3 class="font-heading text-lg font-bold text-ink">Too many marketplaces to check</h3>
        <p class="mt-2 text-sm leading-6 text-slate">
          Sourcing teams lose time switching between sites, re-entering filters, and repeating the same process.
        </p>
      </article>
      <article class="card">
        <h3 class="font-heading text-lg font-bold text-ink">Manual comparison slows decisions</h3>
        <p class="mt-2 text-sm leading-6 text-slate">
          Comparing price, mileage, year, and source details across tabs is slow and error-prone.
        </p>
      </article>
      <article class="card">
        <h3 class="font-heading text-lg font-bold text-ink">Import cost is calculated separately</h3>
        <p class="mt-2 text-sm leading-6 text-slate">
          Duties, shipping, and fees are often estimated outside the workflow, delaying decisions.
        </p>
      </article>
      <article class="card">
        <h3 class="font-heading text-lg font-bold text-ink">Weak-fit listings waste attention</h3>
        <p class="mt-2 text-sm leading-6 text-slate">
          Without fast filtering and prioritization, teams spend time on vehicles that do not match targets.
        </p>
      </article>
      <article class="card md:col-span-2 xl:col-span-2">
        <h3 class="font-heading text-lg font-bold text-ink">Good opportunities are harder to spot</h3>
        <p class="mt-2 text-sm leading-6 text-slate">
          When information is scattered, it becomes harder to identify strong options quickly and act first.
        </p>
      </article>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>
